00:36:19,303 --> 00:36:22,390
instead he hits
the nail on the head hard.

635
00:36:22,391 --> 00:36:26,999
This book is chock full of no-nonsense
exposure of frauds and rip-offs.

636
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:29,211
You'll learn how easily
people can be deceived,

637
00:36:29,212 --> 00:36:31,780
and it can
be a big wake-up call.

638
00:36:31,781 --> 00:36:34,247
If you want to be able to
recognize when someone's taking advantage

639
00:36:34,248 --> 00:36:36,500
of you with a
fraudulent product or service,

640
00:36:36,501 --> 00:36:41,980
expertise in the art of Flim Flam
is your first line of defense.

641
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:48,024
Third, I'm going to recommend a
book that you probably didn't expect,

642
00:36:48,025 --> 00:36:50,725
Mark Twain's The Adventures
of Huckleberry Finn.

643
00:36:50,726 --> 00:36:53,672
Mark Twain was perhaps
the most effective critic

644
00:36:53,673 --> 00:36:56,619
of human ignorance and
folly who ever lived.

645
00:36:56,620 --> 00:36:59,418
Although on its surface it appears
to be an adventure story,

646
00:36:59,419 --> 00:37:01,669
it’s really a collection of quite

